Brae, A. E. (1843). Chimes for house-clocks. <cite>Transactions of the Society, Instituted at London,
for the Encouragement of Arts, Manufactures, and Commerce, 55</cite>. Retrieved from https://archive.org/details/jstor-41326961/

Coleman, <span title="Satis">S.</span> N. (1928). Clock bells. In <cite>Bells: Their history, legends, making, and uses</cite>
(pp. 158â€“168).  Retrieved from https://archive.org/details/bellstheirhistor00cole/
- mentions the "Cambridge Chimes" (i.e., Westminster)

Pearce, <span title="Charles W.">C. W.</span> (1903, December 1). Occasional notes [Letter to the editor].
<cite>Musical Times, 44</cite>(730), 790.  Retrieved from
https://ia600708.us.archive.org/view_archive.php?archive=/22/items/crossref-pre-1909-scholarly-works/10.2307%252F903901.zip&file=10.2307%252F904253.pdf
- letter to the editor from 1903, should be public domain because it's an article published before 1926 and the music was composed before 1925
- gives the melody of the "New College chimes" (but not the note for the hour strike)

Starmer, <span title="William Wooding">W. W.</span> (1917). The clock jacks of England. 
<cite>Proceedings of the Musical Association</cite>.  Retrieved from
https://ia800708.us.archive.org/view_archive.php?archive=/28/items/crossref-pre-1923-scholarly-works/10.1093%252Fjhered%252Fos-8.1.440.zip&file=10.1093%252Fjrma%252F44.1.1.pdf
- paper from 1917, should be public domain because it's an article published before 1926 and the music was composed before 1925
- discusses primarily the human-shaped striking mechanisms but references some chime melodies
- calls the Whittington "the Great St. Mary chimes"
- notes that both Westminster and St. Mary don't have an hour strike that harmonize with the chime melody
- note that the paper was still typeset in old typography (space after opening quotes, space before closing quotes, colons etc.)

